description: TO CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF BENJAMIN K. PIERCE AND OTHERS FOR BREVET PROMOTIONS IN THE ARMY.

TO CONSENT TO THE NOMINATIONS OF BENJAMIN K. PIERCE, THOMAS CHILDS, WM. M. GRAHAM, RICHARD B. LEE, JAMES A. ASHBY, CAMPBELL GRAHAM, WM. S. MAITLAND, AND ALFRED HERBERT, FOR BREVIET PROMOTIONS IN THE ARMY.
TO TABLE THE NOMINATION OF ARCHIBALD HENDERSON AND OTHERS FOR BREVET PROMOTIONS IN THE ARMY AND MARINE CORPS.
TO ADMINISTER THE REQUIRED OATH TO THE HON. AMBROSE H. SEVIER, APPOINTED A SENATOR BY THE GOVERNOR OF ARKANSAS.
TO CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF JOHN CATRON AS ASSOCIATE JUDGE OF THE SUPREME COURT.
TO CONSENT TO THE NOMINATION OF WM. SMITH AS ASSOCIATE JUDGE OF THE SUPREME COURT.

TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF THE NOMINATION OF DENNY MC COBB AS COLLECTOR OF THE CUSTOMS FOR THE DISTRICT AND INSPECTOR OF REVENUE FOR THE PORT OF WALDOBORO, MAINE, UNTIL THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS.

TO AMEND S. 1 (APP. OCT. 2, 1837, 5 STAT L. 201), A BILL POSTPONING PAYMENT OF THE FOURTH INSTALLMENT OF THE STATE DEPOSITS, BY PROVIDING THAT THE THREE FIRST INSTALLMENTS SHALL REMAIN ON DEPOSIT WITH THE STATES UNTIL OTHERWISE DIRECTED BY CONGRESS.

TO AMEND S. 1 BY DIRECTING THAT THE MONEY TO BE DEPOSITED WITH THE STATES UNDER THE 13TH SECTION OF THE ACT OF JUNE 23, 1836, SHALL REMAIN ON DEPOSIT WITH THE STATES UNTIL OTHERWISE DIRECTED BY CONGRESS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 1.
TO PASS S. 1.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION, AS IN COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, OF S. 2, A BILL AUTHORIZING THE SECRETARY OF TREASURY TO ISSUE TREASURY NOTES, IN ORDER TO DELAY ACTION UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MONDAY.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY PROVIDING A REDUCTION OF INTEREST FROM SIX TO THREE PERCENT.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 2.
TO AMEND S. 3 (APP. OCT. 16, 1837, 5 STAT L 205), A BILL AUTHORIZING FURTHER POSTPONEMENT OF PAYMENT ON DUTY BONDS, BY EXTENDING THE TIME OF MAKING PAYMENTS FROM SIX TO NINE MONTHS.

TO AMEND AMEND. TO THE RES. PROVIDING THAT THE RESPECTIVE MEMORIALISTS OUGHT NOT BE GRANTED THEIR REQUEST TO ESTABLISH A NATIONAL BANK, BY INSERTING "THAT IN THE OPINION OF THIS SENATE A CLEAR MAJORITY OF THE PEOPLE OF THE U.S. ARE OPPOSED TO THE ESTABLIHMENT OF A NATIONAL BANK."

TO POSTPONE, AS IN COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, FURTHER CONSIDERATION OF S. 6, A BILL IMPOSING ADDITIONAL DUTIES AS DEPOSITORIES IN CERTAIN CASES ON PUBLIC OFFICERS, UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY OF DECEMBER NEXT.
TO POSTPONE, UNTIL MONDAY NEXT, CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION REJECTING A PETITION FOR A NATIONAL BANK.
TO TABLE THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE NATIONAL BANK.

TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT AS AMENDED TO THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE NATIONAL BANK; WHICH AMENDED AMENDMENT STATES THAT THE SENATE THINKS IT UNNECESSARY AND INEXPEDIENT TO ESTABLISH THE BANK; AND WHICH HERE IS FURTHER AMENDED BY ADDING THAT WHENEVER THE WIL OF THE PEOPLE DESIRES A BANK TO BE ESTABLISHED, IT WILL BE DONE.

TO AMEND THE AMENDED AMENDMENT TO THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE NATIONAL BANK, WHICH AMENDED AMENDMENT STATES THAT THE SENATE THINKS IT INEXPEDIENT TO ESTABLISH A BANK BUT WILL DO SO WHEN THE WILL OF THE PEOPLE DICTATES IT, BY SUBSTITUTING THE STATEMENT HAT A CLEAR MAJORITY OF THE PEOPLE DO NOT DESIRE THE ESTABLISHMENT OF THE BANK AND THE REQUEST OF THE PETITIONERS OUGHT NOT BE GRANTED.
TO PASS THE RESOLUTION CONCERNING THE NATIONAL BANK AS AMENDED.
TO CONCUR WITH HOUSE AMENDMENT TO S. 1, PAYMENT OF DEPOSITS TO STATES UNDER ACT OF JUNE 23, 1836.

TO AMEND S. 6 BY REPEALING THE RESOLUTION OF 1816, WHICH AUTHORIZES THE RECEIVING OF NOTES OF SPECIE-PAYING BANKS FOR PAYMENTS DUE THE GOVERNMENT, IN GRADUAL STEPS FROM DEC. 31, 1839 UNTIL DEC. 31, 1841, AT WHICH TIME ALL SUMS DUE THE GOVERNMENT SHALL BEPAID IN GOLD OR SILVER OR IN AUTHORIZED GOVERNMENT NOTES, AND ALL SUMS SHALL BE PAID OUT BY THE GOVERNMENT OR ITS AGENTS MADE IN THE SAME MANNER.
TO AMEND S. 6 BY MAKING BANKS SPECIAL DEPOSITORIES FOR ACCRUED U.S. REVENUE.

TO AMEND, AS IN COMMITTEE OF THE WHOLE, S. 6, BY STRIKING OUT ALL AFTER THE ENACTING CLAUSE AND INSERTING A PROVISION THAT UNTIL RESUMPTION OF SPECIE PAYMENT BY THE BANKS, THE SEC. OF THE TREASURY SHALL MAKE DEPOSITS TO ACCURE U.S. REVENUE IN CONVENIENTL LOCATED, INCORPORATED BANKS.
TO AMEND AMENDMENT PERMITTING TREASURY NOTES OF ANY DENOMINATION TO BE ACCEPTED AT THE PLACE WHERE THEY ARE PAYABLE, IN PAYMENT OF PUBLIC DUES.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 6.
TO ADJOURN AND END DEBATE ON S. 6.
TO PASS S. 6.

TO AMEND S. 11 (APP. OCT. 12, 1837, 5 STAT 204), A BILL REGULATING THE FEES OF DISTRICT ATTORNEYS IN CERTAIN CASES, BY REQUIRING EXTENSION OF PAYMENTS ON BONDS GIVEN FOR DUTIES ON IMPORTS, TO BE MADE ACCORDING TO THE SECRETARY OF THE TREASURY'S INSTRUCTINS.

TO RECOMMIT S. 11, (APP. OCT. 12, 1837, 5 STAT 204), A BILL REGULATING THE FEES OF DISTRICT ATTORNEYS IN CERTAIN CASES, WITH INSTRUCTIONS THAT THE COMMITTEE ON FINANCE REPORT BILL BACK PROVIDING FOR REASONABLE RENUMERATION TO DISTRICT ATTORNEYS FOR SERVIES ALREADING RENDERED.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE RATIFICATION OF THE GENERAL CONVENTION OF PEACE, FRIENDSHIP, COMMERCE, AND NAVIGATION BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE PERU-BOLIVIAN CONFEDERATION, CONCLUDED ON NOV. 30, 1836.
TO POSTPONE UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY OF DECEMBER NEXT, CONSIDERATION OF S. 5, A BILL AUTHORIZING THE DEPOSITING OF MERCHANDISE IN PUBLIC STORES.
TO AMEND S. 5 BY GIVING IMPORTERS THE OPTION TO LAND GOODS, WAREHOUSE THEM, AND PLACE GOODS UPON WHICH SUCH DUTIES ARE CHARGEABLE IN STORAGE PURSUANT TO THE PROVISIONS OF THIS ACT.
TO AMEND H.R. 2 (APP. OCT. 12, 1837, 5 STAT 201), A BILL AUTHORIZING THE ISSUANCE OF TREASURY NOTES, BY FIXING THEIR MINIMUM VALUE AT $100.
TO PASS H.R. 2, (APP. OCT. 12, 1827, 5 STAT 201), A BILL AUTHORIZING THE ISSUANCE OF TREASURY NOTES.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF S. 5 UNTIL THE FIRST MONDAY IN DECEMBER NEXT.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 5.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE RATIFICATION OF THE ORIGINAL ARTICLES IN THE TREATY WITH THE MIAMI INDIANS OF OCT. 23, 1834, AND THE AMENDMENT THERETO PROPOSED BY THE COMMITTEE OF INDIAN AFFAIRS.
TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO THE RATIFICATION OF THE TREATY WITH THE MIAMI INDIANS OF OCT. 23, 1837.

TO ADVISE AND CONSENT TO AN AMENDMENT IN NATURE OF A SUBSTITUTE FOR THE TREATY BETWEEN THE U.S. AND THE MIAMI INDIANS, OF OCT. 23, 1834 (PROVIDED THAT THE TRIBES SHALL IN GENERAL COUNCIL AGREE TO SIGN SAME); SUBSTITUTE PROPOSES TO RATIFY SAID TREATY WITHTHE MIAMI INDIANS, FIXES THE CEDING OF LANDS TO THE U.S
TO POSTPONE INDEFINITELY THE NOMINATION OF THOMAS WILSON AS INDIAN AGENT.
TO TABLE A MOTION TO RECEIVE A PETITION BY NEW JERSEY WOMEN, PRAYING FOR THE IMMEDIATE ABOLITION OF SLAVERY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.

TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION UNTIL THE SECOND MONDAY OF JANUARY NEXT, OF S. 33 (APP. JULY 7, 1838, 5 STAT 309), RESTRAINING THE ISSUANCE AND CIRCULATION OF SMALL NOTES AS CURRENCY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.
TO COMMIT S. 33 TO THE COMMITTEE ON THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.
TO AMEND SECTION 2 OF S. 33 BY PROVIDING THAT A DEFENDANT MUST GO TO COURT AND COMMENCE AN ACTION FOR THE RECOVERY OF DAMAGES, INSTEAD OF INSTITUTING SUMMARY PROCEEDINGS.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 33.
TO PASS S. 33.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT AND THIRD READING OF S. 5, A BILL AUTHORIZING THE STATES TO TAX ANY LANDS WITHIN THEIR LIMITS SOLD BY U.S.

TO AMEND S. 21, A BILL ALTERING AND AMENDING THE ACT PROVIDING FOR THE PUNISHMENT OF CERTAIN CRIMES AGAINST THE U.S., APPROVED APR. 30, 1790, BY SUBSTITUTING HARD LABOR FOR LIFE FOR THE DEATH PENALTY.

TO AMEND S. 31, A BILL PROVIDING FOR THE SETTLEMENT OF THE CLAIM OF EXECUTRIX OF THE ESTATE OF RICHARD MEADE, BY ELIMINATING THE PROVISION THAT IF THE CLAIM IS NOT ALLOWABLE IT SHALL BE SO REPORTED AT THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGRESS.

TO AMEND S. 31, A BILL PROVIDING FOR THE SETTLEMENT OF THE CLAIM OF EXECUTRIX OF THE ESTATE OF RICHARD MEADE, BY PROVIDING THAT THE BOARD EXAMINE THIS CLAIM AS IT EXISTED ORIGINALLY AGAINST SPAIN, AND REPORT BACK TO THE SENATE AT THE NEXT SESSION OF CONGESS.

TO AMEND THE FIRST RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, FREEDOM OF SPEECH AND THE PRESS, BY STATING THAT THE STATES RETAIN SOLE RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES OVER THEIR INSTITUTIONS AND POLICE, AND THAT ONE STATE SHALL NOT, FOR MORAL OR RELIGIOUS REASONS, INTERFRE WITH ANY OTHER STATE.

TO PASS THE FIRST RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IN THE ADOPTION OF THE FEDERAL CONSTITUTION, THE INDIVIDUAL STATES ACTED AS FREE STATES AND VOLUNTARILY ENTERED THE UNION FOR INCREASED SECURITY AGAINST ALL DOMESTIC AND FOREIGN DANGERS, AND FR ENJOYMENT OF NATURAL, POLITICAL AND SOCIAL ADVANTAGES.

TO AMEND THE SECOND RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY BY ELIMINATING THE CLAUSE WHICH STATES THAT MEDDLING BY ANY ONE OR MORE STATES IN THE DOMESTIC INSTITUTIONS OF OTHER STATES WILL TEND TO WEAKEN OR DESTROY THE UNION STATES.

TO PASS THE SECOND RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IN DELEGATING A PORTION OF THEIR POWERS TO THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT, THE STATES RETAINED THE EXCLUSIVE RIGHT OVER THEIR OWN DOMESTIC INSTITUTIONS AND POLICE, AND THAT ANY INTERFERENCE BY OTHER TATES IS SUBVERSIVE TO THE CONSTITUTION.

TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT TO THE THIRD RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, SO AS TO PROVIDE THAT THIS RESOLUTION SHOULD NOT BE INTERPRETED AS AN EFFORT ON THE PART OF CONGRESS TO IMPAIR THE FREEDOMS OF SPEECH, PRESS, OR PETITION.

TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT TO THE THIRD RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, BY DECLARING THE RIGHT OF FREE SPEECH AND PUBLICATION OF OPINION CONCERNING ANY STATE, AND THAT THOSE EXERCISING SUCH RIGHTS ARE RESPONSIBLE ONLY TO THE STATE IN WHICH THE RIGHT IS EXERCIED.

TO AMEND THE THIRD RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, FREEDOM OF SPEECH AND THE PRESS, AND THE RIGHT OF PETITION, BY CHANGING THE WORDING TO READ "THE PEOPLE OF THE U.S.," RATHER THAN "THE SEVERAL STATES OF THIS UNION AS A COMMON AGENT."

TO PASS THE THIRD RESOLUTION, AS AMENDED, CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IT IS THE DUTY OF THE GOVERNMENT TO UPHOLD THE RIGHTS FOR MUTUAL SECURITY AND PROSPERITY; TO EXERCISE ITS POWERS SO AS NOT TO INTERFERE WITH THE DOMESTIC INSTITUTIONS OF THE STATE; AND TO PREVENT A STATE FROM ATTACKING, WEAKENING OR DESTROYING THE DOMESTIC INSTITUTIONS OF ANOTHER STATE.

TO PASS THE FOURTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT DOMESTIC SLAVERY AS IT EXISTS IN THE SOUTH AND WEST COMPRISES AN IMPORTANT PART OF THEIR DOMESTIC INSTITUTIONS AND SHOULD BE FREE FROM ATTACK BY OTHER STATES.

TO AMEND THE FIFTH RESOLUTION PROTESTING AGAINST THE ABOLITION OF SLAVERY IN THE TERRITORIES AND THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, BY REWORDING THE RESOLUTION TO STATE THAT IT WOULD BE INEXPEDIENT AND DANGEROUS TO THE UNION TO ABOLISH SLAVERY IN THE DISTRICT OF OLUMBIA OR ANY PART OF THE COUNTRY WHERE IT NOW EXISTS.

TO SUBSTITUTE THE AMENDED RESOLUTION STATING THAT IT WOULD BE INEXPEDIENT AND DANGEROUS TO THE UNION TO ABOLISH SLAVERY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA OR ANY PART OF THE COUN- TRY WHERE IT NOW EXISTS, FOR THE FIFTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY.

TO PASS THE 5TH RESOLUTION AS AMENDED CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IT WOULD BE INEXPEDIENT AND DANGEROUS TO THE UNION TO ABOLISH SLAVERY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA OR ANY PART OF THE COUNTRY WHERE IT NOW EXISTS, AND THAT TERRITORIES BE ALLOWED TO DEIDE THEMSELVES ABOUT SLAVERY WITHIN THEIR BOUNDRIES.

TO AMEND THE SIXTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IT WOULD BE INEXPEDIENT TO ABOLISH SLAVERY IN INDIAN TERRITORY OR IN FLORIDA SINCE IT WOULD ALARM THE SLAVE STATES, BY STRIKING OUT INDIAN TERRITORY FROM THE RESOLUTION.

TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT TO THE SIXTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, STATING THAT IT WOULD BE INEXPEDIENT TO ABOLISH SLAVERY IN INDIAN TERRITORY OR FLORIDA SINCE IT WOULD ALARM THE SLAVE STATES, BY SUBSTITUTING THAT ANY INTERFERENCE WITH SLAVERY IN THE TERITORIES WOULD INHIBIT THE RIGHTS AND INTERESTS OF THE INHABITANTS AND THE SECURITY OF THE SLAVE STATES; AND THAT THE ISSUE OF SLAVERY WILL BE DECIDED BY THE TERRITORIES UPON ENTERING THE UNION.

TO PASS THE SIXTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY WHICH PROVIDES THAT ANY ATTEMPT BY CONGRESS TO ABOLISH SLAVERY, IN ANY TERRITORY WHERE IT NOW EXISTS, WOULD CAUSE SERIOUS ALARM AND APPREHENSION IN SUCH STATES AND WOULD BE A VIOLA- TION OF GOOD FAITH AS NOABOLISHMENT WAS ASKED, AND THAT TERRITORIES UPON THEIR ADMITTANCE INTO THE UNION SHALL DECIDE THE QUESTION FOR THEMSELVES.

TO TABLE THE SEVENTH RESOLUTION CONCERNING SLAVERY, WHICH DEFINES THE NATURE OF THE UNION BETWEEN SLAVE AND FREE STATES AS RESTING UPON EQUALITY OF RIGHTS BETWEEN THEM, AND FURTHER STATES THAT TO REFUSE TO EXTEND SLAVERY IN THE WEST AND SOUTH VIOLATES TH RIGHTS OF THESE STATES.
TO TABLE A RESOLUTION STATING THAT NOTHING IN THE FOREGOING RESOLUTIONS CONCERNING SLAVERY IS MEANT TO IMPAIR THE FREE- DOM OF SPEECH, PRESS OR PETITION AS SECURED IN THE CONSTITUTION.
TO TABLE CONSIDERATION OF THE RESOLUTION PROTESTING AGAINST THE ADMISSION OF TEXAS OR ANY SLAVE STATE INTO THE UNION.  GLOBE DESCRIBES RESOLUTION AS ABOLISHING SLAVERY IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA.
TO TABLE THE MOTION TO RECONSIDER VOTE BY WHICH S. 6 WAS MADE THE ORDER OF THE DAY FOR TUESDAY FORTNIGHT.
TO RECONSIDER VOTE BY WHICH TUESDAY FORTNIGHT WAS FIXED AS THE DAY FOR CONSIDERING S. 6.

TO RECOMMIT S. 31, A BILL RELATING TO THE CLAIM OF THE EXECUTRIX OF THE ESTATE OF RICHARD MEADE, TO THE COMMITTEE ON CLAIMS WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO INVESTIGATE IT THOROUGHLY AND AMEND IT BY STRIKING OUT SECTION 2.
TO PASS S. 31, A BILL RELATING TO THE CLAIM OF THE EXECUTRIX OF THE ESTATE OF RICHARD MEADE.

TO AMEND S. 1, (APP. JULY 7, 1838, 5 STAT 304), A BILL PROVIDING FOR THE BETTER SECURITY OF LIVES OF PASSENGERS ON VESSELS, BY PROVIDING THAT ANY OFFICER WHO SHALL BE GUILTY OF RACING WITH ANY STEAMBOAT, SHALL BE GUILTY OF A HIGH MISDEMEANOR.
TO RECOMMIT S. 138, (APP. JULY 5, 1838, 5 STAT 256), A BILL INCREASING THE ARMY, TO COMMITTEE ON MILITARY OFFICERS, WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO ADD THREE REGIMENTS.
TO ADJOURN AND TERMINATE DEBATE ON S. 2 (APP. JUNE 22, 1838, 5 STAT 251), A BILL GRANTING THE RIGHT OF PRE-EMPTION TO ACTUAL SETTLERS ON PUBLIC LANDS.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY REFUSING THE RIGHT OF PRE-EMPTION TO FAMILIES WHO TOOK POSSESSION BEFORE THE RESOLUTION OF THE INDIAN TITLE TO THE LAND.
TO AMEND THE AMENDMENT TO S. 2 BY DENYING PRE-EMPTION TO SETTLERS ON LANDS TO WHICH THE INDIAN TITLE HAD NOT BEEN RESOLVED SIX MONTHS PRIOR TO DECEMBER FIRST LAST.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY GIVING EVERY MAN WHO WAS AN ACTUAL SETTLER ON THE PUBLIC LANDS ON THE FIRST OF DECEMBER LAST, A PRE-EMPTION, PROVIDED THE INDIAN TITLE WAS RESOLVED AT THE TIME OF SETTLEMENT.

TO AMEND S. 2 BY ELIMINATING THAT PART OF BILL RELATING TO SETTLEMENT AND BY INSERTING A PROVISION REQUIRING RESIDENCE THEREON BEFORE THE FIRST DAY OF DECEMBER 1837, THE CULTIVATION OF AT LEAST ONE ACRE, AND CONTINUED RESIDENCE AND CULTIVATION TO THIS TIE.
TO POSTPONE CONSIDERATION OF S. 2 UNTIL MONDAY IN ORDER TO GIVE MEMBERS TIME TO LOOK INTO THE RULES OF THE GENERAL LAND OFFICE.
TO ADJOURN AND TERMINATE DEBATE ON S. 2.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY REQUIRING THAT PRIOR TO ANY ENTRIES BEING MADE UNDER THIS ACT, PROOF OF SETTLEMENT BE MADE UNDER THE RULES NOW IN FORCE.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY PROVIDING THAT THE PRIVILEGES OF THE ACT SHALL APPLY ONLY TO THOSE WHO WERE CITIZENS PRIOR TO DECEMBER 1, 1837.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY PROHIBITING SETTLEMENT AFTER DECEMBER 1, 1837.
TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING CONSIDERATION OF S. 2.
TO ADJOURN, MOTION MADE DURING DEBATE ON S. 2; VICE PRESIDENT VOTING IN THE NEGATIVE.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY PROVIDING THAT THE ACT SHALL NOT APPLY TO THE LAND CEDED BY THE TREATY OF 1837 WITH THE MIAMI INDIANS.
TO AMEND S. 2 BY PROVIDING THAT NO PERSON SHALL BE ENTITLED TO ANY RIGHTS OR A PATENT UNTIL HE PAYS AT LEAST ONE-HALF OF THE REAL VALUE OF THE LAND IN ADDITION TO THE STATUTE MINIMUM PRICE.
TO ORDER ENGROSSMENT OF S. 2.
TO PASS S. 84, A BILL MAKING FINAL ADJUSTMENT AND SETTLEMENT OF CLAIMS TO LAND DERIVED UNDER GRANTS TO BARON BASTROP AND OTHERS.
TO PASS S. 2.

TO AMEND S. 157, A BILL IMPOSING DUTIES AS DEPOSITORIES ON CERTAIN PUBLIC OFFICERS AND REGULATING THE DISPOSAL OF U.S. PUBLIC MONEYS, BY FIXING THE SALARY OF THE RECEIVER GENERAL IN NEW YORK AT $3,000 PER ANNUM.

TO AMEND S. 157, BY PROVIDING THAT ALL SUMS PAYABLE TO THE U.S. BE PAID IN LEGAL CURRENCY.

THAT WHEN SENATE ADJOURNS, IT DO SO UNTIL MONDAY NEXT.
